result.execSummary:
The defendant Matthew H Pinzer was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Matthew H Pinzer is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges. On one or more other charges, Matthew H Pinzer was found not guilty. These charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Matthew H Pinzer is presumed innocent of the not guilty charges.

  • Matthew H Pinzer was found guilty of Possess Drug Paraphernalia, an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 961.573(1).
  • Matthew H Pinzer was found guilty of Possession of Narcotic Drugs, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(am).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Def in person & by Atty Alyssa Armbrust. Atty Sandra Jo Giernoth appeared for State. Reconvene, jury not present. Discussion between court and counsel on instructions and verdicts. Atty Armbrust moves for directed verdict on count #1. Motion denied. Jury enters. Court instructs jury. Closing arguments by counsel. Final instructions to jury. Bailif sworn and jury exits for deliberations. Reconvene with jury present. Foreperson identified. Court reads jury verdicts into the record. Jury finds defendant not guilty of count #1; guilty of count #2 (count #3 of Information)  and guilty of count #3 (count #4 of information). Court polls jurors individually. Court thanks jury and excuses them. State moves for judgment on verdicts. Atty Armbrust moves for judgment on verdict as to count #1. Court grants judgment on jury verdicts. Sentencing hearing scheduled for May 2, 2016 at 11:15 am. Record closed.

Def in person & by Atty Alyssa Armbrust.  Atty Sandra Jo Giernoth appeared for State. Record opened, jury panel not present. Also present, SPD investigator Heather Allen. Letter filed on 4-14-16 by defendant requesting new counsel, a copy of which was supplied to both counsel. Atty Armbrust indicates she has met with def and issue resolved. Def confirms he is prepared to proceed with Atty Armbrust. Discussion between court and counsel on trial issues. Jury will not be permitted to take notes. Given that count #2 was previously dismissed, court will refer to the charges before the jury as counts #1, #2 and #3 rather than counts #1, #3 and #4. Court takes under advisement whether statements made to law enforcement during a phone conversation with def will be allowed. Argument by counsel on prior record of witnesses. Court rules that prior record of State's witness for purposes of trial testimony is two. Jury panel enters. Panel sworn and 20 called to box. Voir dire by court and counsel. Counsel selects jury. Jury sworn and balance of panel excused. Jury admonished and excused. Reconvene, jury not present. Court rules that the State may introduce evidence that a phone call was made by pholice to def prior to arrest and the subject matter of the conversation but not introduce the portion of the statement regarding drugs in the house. State permitted to keep court officer prseent during trial. Other witnesses are ordered sequestered. Jury enters. Court gives preliminary instructions to jury. Opening statements by counsel. Witness: Kevin William P.; Officer Cori Richard Whipple (HPD). Jury excused. Argument by counsel on an objection. Questioning of Officer Whipple conducted outside presennce of jury. Jury returns. Continued testimony of same witness. Witness: Pamela S. Eggert (HPD evidence custodian); Megann McMahon (crime lab analyst). Jury excused. Exhibits addressed. Reconvene, jury not present. Discussion between court and defendant regarding def's right to testify. Discussion regarding def's prior record. Court rules that for purposes of trial, def can testify to 4 prior convictions. Jury enters. Witness: Matthew P. Defense rests. Court admonishes jury and excuses them for the day. Recess.
